posts.name: Scott Coursin
posts.cooked: Thank you for making this tool available, we love it.  I am seeing version 2025.2.3 in vendor dependencies, but no corresponding release in Github.  Is this release ready?

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: Yes it is.  Generally speaking (in FRC at least), any version [year].1.0 or higher is a valid non-beta release for the current season.  Newer releases will fix bugs or add new features, so it’s often worth keeping up to date

posts.name: alst
posts.cooked:
The question is whether that release is finalized because it isn’t currently on GitHub:

A simple yet powerful path planning tool for FRC robots - mjansen4857/pathplanner

A simple yet powerful path planning tool for FRC robots - Tags · mjansen4857/pathplanner

This is probably a question better left to the PathPlanner maintainers.

posts.name: Michael Jansen
posts.cooked: I only make releases on the GitHub for GUI versions. The GUI and PPLib technically have different versioning. A PPLib 2025.X update might not have any GUI changes so it doesn’t make sense to release a new GUI version.

posts.name: alst
posts.cooked: Makes sense, although there is still the question of how someone could figure out what’s new in v2025.2.3 of the library, since there isn’t a tag for it and the old pathplannerlib repo is no longer in use. (It’s possible there is a simple answer to this question - I haven’t used PathPlanner much personally.)

posts.name: Michael Jansen
posts.cooked:
There’s a changelog that I’ve been forgetting to update

I’ll go through and retroactively update it soon.

posts.name: Scott Coursin
posts.cooked: OK, thanks.  We are a C++ team and we were having some issues with mirroring, 2025.2.3 seemed to help.
